[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.1 BasicNeeds[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]BasicNeeds is an international development organisation that was founded in 2000 by Chris Underhill MBE with the aim of bringing about lasting change in the lives of people with mental illness and epilepsy, and their family members.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]BasicNeeds’ purpose is to 
[normal]enable people with mental illness or epilepsy and their families to live and work successfully in their communities [bold]by combining health, socio-economic and community orientated solutions with changes in policy, practice and resource allocation. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]By delivering the BasicNeeds Model for Mental Health and Development, BasicNeeds has worked with hundreds of national and international partners and reached more than 
[normal]half a million[bold] people with mental illness and epilepsy, and their family members.  Based on its community generated experience and knowledge, BasicNeeds has challenged the status quo, leading and affecting change in national and global policy and practice.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]BasicNeeds has had a significant impact on policy and systems change 
[normal]on local, regional, 
[normal]national 
[normal]and international 
[normal]level
[normal]s and has worked closely with the 
[normal]World Health Organisation. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]BasicNeeds empowers people with lived experience of mental illness to come together collectively into 
[normal]self-help
[normal] groups (SHGs) and 
[normal]self-advocate
[normal] for their needs and their rights. In Ghana, a national association of people with mental illness and their caregivers was founded
[normal] from SHGs.
[normal] 
[normal]Together with
[normal] BasicNeeds, 
[normal]the association 
[normal]played a key role in influencing the passage of a new mental health bill that was
[normal] finally
[normal] approved in 2011. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]BasicNeeds has also played a critical role in national reform in Kenya, Laos PDR, India, Uganda, Tanzania, Sri Lanka, and Vietnam. At a global level, BasicNeeds has influenced the development of the WHO’s mhGAP Intervention Guide. It 
[normal]lends its
[normal] expertise to The Lancet Movement for Global Mental Health (which Chris Underhill leads), the PRIME global research coalition in mental health, 
[normal]National
[normal] Institute of Mental Health t
[normal]he WHO Global Forum of Mental Health, and two WHO steering committees. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]BasicNeeds has conducted a 
[normal] number 
[normal]of research studies on both mental health and development policy and practice, and recently co-authored a case study on the implementation of the BasicNeeds model in Nepal that was published in PLoS Medicine, a peer reviewed journal.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]2.2[bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]BasicNeeds’ a[bold]ssociation with DFID[bold] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Since BasicNeeds was established in 2000, DFID has provided significant funding through its grants schemes to BasicNeeds programmes in low and middle income countries (LMIC).  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I
[normal]n 2013 
[normal]BasicNeeds established an
[normal] important relationship with DFID 
[normal]as, via a bilateral aid programme, 
[normal]BasicNeeds Ghana 
[normal]began 
[normal]providing its expertise to the government of 
[normal]Ghana to support the implementation of their 2011 Mental Health Act.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]BasicNeeds is also a partner in the DFID funded research on mental health, called 
[normal]the 
[normal]Programme for Improving Mental Health Care (PRIME) led by Cape Town University. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Along with the European Union and Grand Challenges Canada, 
[normal]DF
[normal]ID is
[normal] one of the few funders making an effort to invest in mental health. Currently the investment tends to be focused on research but notably DFID and the European Union, through supporting BasicNeeds programmes
[normal], have
[normal] supported service delivery. There is a challenge to translate the research into much needed services delivery, see our recent blog for comment on this:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]http://www.huffingtonpost.com/basicneeds/results-in-mental-health_b_4254150.html
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3 [bold]Mental health[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Mental illness is seen as both a cause, and a consequence of poverty
[normal] and ill-health
[normal].  Globally, an estimated 13% of all disease is attributable to mental health disorders, and neuropsychiatric conditions contribute the most to this overall burden: more 
[normal]than either cardiovascular disease or cancer.
[normal] As highlighted by the latest Global Burden of Disease Report, mental illness is projected to be the leading burden of disease by 2030. As Alan Lopez, one of the leading contributors to the report noted, “
[normal]mental health is perhaps one of the most neglected of neglected diseases in global health
[normal]”.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Almost three quarters of those suffering from mental illness live in low and middle income countries
[normal], where up to 85% of people with severe mental health conditions do not have access to much needed mental health treatment (the figure for high income countries is 35-50%).  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Mental health is extremely under-resourced with the complete absence of mental health budgets in almost a third of countries.  In LMIC there is a severe lack of psychiatrists, and the majority of people resort to consulting traditional healers that can result in human rights abuses.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Poverty brings with it heightened stress, social exclusion, malnutrition, violence and trauma, all of which contribute to mental illness.  It is a vicious circle, as those with mental illness experience widespread stigma and discrimination, suffer violence and abuse, they find it harder to get work, get an education or contribute to family and community.  They are more prone to other forms of illness and disease, and find it harder to access health care.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Impaired mental health can lead to disability or premature death. 
[normal]A mental health condition is therefore considered a disability if it has a long-term effect on normal day-to-day activity.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]3.1 [bold]The strength of the evidence base[bold] on ‘what works’ in development [bold]programmes involving disabilit[bold]y [bold]&#xa0;[bold]BasicNeeds
