[normal]3.3 [bold]The role of disabled beneficiaries in planning, managing and monitoring DFID [bold]policy and programmes[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]BasicNeeds
[normal] believes 
[normal]to ensure sustainable outcomes
[normal] people affected by mental illness or epilepsy, particularly those who are most marginalised and living in poverty, 
[normal]must
[normal] participate in and lead solutions that will transform their lives.
[normal]  
[normal]The design and delivery of all 
[normal]BasicNeeds 
[normal]programmes funded by DFID 
[normal]are underpinned
[normal] by this belief
[normal] 
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]BasicNeeds
[normal] has a rich experience of 
[normal]supporting the development of SHGs of people with mental illness and epilepsy and their carers. These are sustainable independent registered structures and are empowered to self-advocate. 
[normal] 
[normal]As previously described a national users association has developed in Ghana as a result of the
[normal] SHG movement
[normal] and the voices and advoc
[normal]acy that this association brings
[normal] to the
[normal] delivery of the
[normal] DFID bilateral project 
[normal]mentioned is notable
[normal]. 
[normal] This development was supported through funding from Comic Relief.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As well as supporting the development of the government capacity to provide mental health services the bilateral project
[normal] supports
[normal] all the elements of the
[normal] implementation of the BasicNeeds Model. This includes
[normal] the development of a further 
[normal]1237 community based SHGs and 175 district service users/care-givers association
[normal]s in Ghana that will significantly strengthen the Users movement
[normal], 
[normal]contributing to ensuring services meet their needs and  that change is 
[normal]sustainable
[normal] 
[normal].
[normal]We recommend that DFID consult disabled people’s organisations (including associations of people with mental illness) on new policy. Meaningful consultation with these civil society 
[normal]groups should
[normal] take place using
[normal] appropriate 
[normal]methodology
[normal]. Through our work we have notably developed
[normal] participatory methodologies
[normal] 
[normal]that ensure the inclusion of people with mental illness and epilepsy
[normal] 
[normal]such as Participatory Data Analysis
[normal]; these are described in the references below. 
[normal]Consultations can be f
[normal]acilitated when required by NGOs 
[normal]with experience as in the case of BasicNeeds
[normal] 
[normal]or initiatives such as participate 
[normal](
[normal]http://www.participate2015.org
[normal])
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]. T
[normal]his should be properly resourced and time built into the process for this to happen
[normal].
